# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: packet-switching
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] Circuit switching originated in analog telephone networks where the network created a dedicated circuit between two telephones for the duration of a telephone call.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] It contrasts with message switching and packet switching used in modern digital networks in which the trunklines between switching centres carry data between many different nodes in the form of data packets without dedicated circuits.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] The defining example of a circuit-switched network is the early analogue telephone network.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] When a call is made from one telephone to another, switches within the telephone exchanges create a continuous wire circuit between the two telephones for as long as the call lasts.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] In circuit switching, the bit delay is constant during a connection (as opposed to packet switching, where packet queues may cause varying and potentially indefinitely long packet transfer delays).
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] No circuit can be degraded by competing users because it is protected from use by other callers until the circuit is released and a new connection is set up.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] Even if no actual communication is taking place, the channel remains reserved and protected from competing users.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] While circuit switching is commonly used for connecting voice circuits, the concept of a dedicated path persisting between two communicating parties or nodes can be extended to signal content other than voice.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] The advantage of using circuit switching is that it provides for continuous transfer without the overhead associated with packets, making maximal use of available bandwidth for that communication.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] One disadvantage is that it can be relatively inefficient because unused capacity guaranteed to a connection cannot be used by other connections on the same network.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] In addition, calls cannot be established or will be dropped if the circuit is broken.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] For call setup and control (and other administrative purposes), it is possible to use a separate dedicated signalling channel from the end node to the network.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] ISDN is one such service that uses a separate signalling channel while plain old telephone service (POTS) does not.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] Early telephone exchanges were a suitable example of circuit switching.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] The subscriber would ask the operator to connect to another subscriber, whether on the same exchange or via an inter-exchange link and another operator.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] The result was a physical electrical connection between the two subscribers' telephones for the duration of the call.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] The copper wire used for the connection could not be used to carry other calls at the same time, even if the subscribers were in fact not talking and the line was silent.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] In circuit switching, a route and its associated bandwidth is reserved from source to destination, making circuit switching relatively inefficient since capacity is reserved whether or not the connection is in continuous use.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] Circuit switching contrasts with message switching and packet switching.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] Both of these methods can make better use of available network bandwidth between multiple communication sessions under typical conditions in data communication networks.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] Message switching routes messages in their entirety, one hop at a time, that is, store and forward of the entire message.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] Packet switching divides the data to be transmitted into packets transmitted through the network independently.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] Instead of being dedicated to one communication session at a time, network links are shared by packets from multiple competing communication sessions, resulting in the loss of the quality of service guarantees that are provided by circuit switching.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] Packet switching can be based on connection-oriented communication or connectionless communication.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] That is, based on virtual circuits or datagrams.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] Virtual circuits use packet switching technology that emulates circuit switching, in the sense that the connection is established before any packets are transferred, and packets are delivered in order.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] Connection-less packet switching divides the data to be transmitted into packets, called datagrams, transmitted through the network independently.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] Each datagram is labelled with its destination and a sequence number for ordering related packets, precluding the need for a dedicated path to help the packet find its way to its destination.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] Each datagram is dispatched independently and each may be routed via a different path.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] At the destination, the original message is reordered based on the packet number to reproduce the original message.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] As a result, datagram packet switching networks do not require a circuit to be established and allow many pairs of nodes to communicate concurrently over the same channel.
[src:packet-switching/circuit-switching] Multiplexing multiple telecommunications connections over the same physical conductor has been possible for a long time, but each channel on the multiplexed link was either dedicated to one call at a time or it was idle between calls.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] In telecommunications and computer networking, a **network packet** is a formatted unit of data carried by a packet-switched network.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] A packet consists of control information and user data; the latter is also known as the *payload*.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] Control information provides data for delivering the payload (e.g., source and destination network addresses, error detection codes, or sequencing information).
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] Typically, control information is found in packet headers and trailers.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] In packet switching, the bandwidth of the transmission medium is shared between multiple communication sessions, in contrast to circuit switching, in which circuits are preallocated for the duration of one session and data is typically transmitted as a continuous bit stream.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] In the seven-layer OSI model of computer networking, *packet* strictly refers to a protocol data unit at layer 3, the network layer.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] A data unit at layer 2, the data link layer, is a *frame*.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] In layer 4, the transport layer, the data units are *segments* and *datagrams*.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] Thus, in the example of TCP/IP communication over Ethernet, a TCP segment is carried in one or more IP packets, which are each carried in one or more Ethernet frames.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] The basis of the packet concept is the postal letter: the header is like the envelope, the payload is the entire content inside the envelope, and the footer would be the signature at the bottom.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] Network design can achieve two major results by using packets: *error detection* and *multiple host addressing*.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] Communications protocols use various conventions for distinguishing the elements of a packet and for formatting the user data.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] For example, in Point-to-Point Protocol, the packet is formatted in 8-bit bytes, and special characters are used to delimit elements.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] Other protocols, like Ethernet, establish the start of the header and data elements by their location relative to the start of the packet.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] Some protocols format the information at a bit level instead of a byte level.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] , the source address of the sending host, and the destination address of the receiving host.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] to detect errors that occur during transmission.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] At the transmitter, the calculation is performed before the packet is sent.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] When received at the destination, the checksum is recalculated, and compared with the one in the packet.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] If discrepancies are found, the packet may be corrected or discarded.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] due to these discards is dealt with by the network protocol.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] In some cases, modifications of the network packet may be necessary while routing, in which cases checksums are recalculated.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] If nothing was done, eventually the number of packets circulating would build up until the network was congested to the point of failure.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] If the field reaches zero, routing has failed, and the packet is discarded.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] There may be a field to identify the overall packet length.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] However, in some types of networks, the length is implied by the duration of the transmission.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] It is often desirable to carry multiple communication protocols on a network.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] A protocol identifier field specifies a packet's protocol and allows the protocol stack to process many types of packets.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] which can prioritize some types of packets above others.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] This field indicates which packet queue should be used; a high-priority queue is emptied more quickly than lower-priority queues at points in the network where congestion is occurring.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] In general, the payload is the data that is carried on behalf of an application.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] It is usually of variable length, up to a maximum that is set by the network protocol and sometimes the equipment on the route.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] When necessary, some networks can break a larger packet into smaller packets.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] IP packets are composed of a header and payload.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] The header consists of fixed and optional fields.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] The payload appears immediately after the header.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] However, an IP packet is often carried as the payload inside an Ethernet frame, which has its own header and trailer.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] Per the end-to-end principle, IP networks do not provide guarantees of delivery, non-duplication, or in-order delivery of packets.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] However, it is common practice to layer a reliable transport protocol such as Transmission Control Protocol on top of the packet service to provide such protection.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] The Consultative Committee for Space Data Systems (CCSDS) packet telemetry standard defines the protocol used for the transmission of spacecraft instrument data over the deep-space channel.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] Under this standard, an image or other data sent from a spacecraft instrument is transmitted using one or more packets.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] Packetized elementary stream (PES) is a specification associated with the MPEG-2 standard that allows an elementary stream to be divided into packets.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] The elementary stream is packetized by encapsulating sequential data bytes from the elementary stream between PES packet headers.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] A typical method of transmitting elementary stream data from a video or audio encoder is to first create PES packets from the elementary stream data and then to encapsulate these PES packets inside an MPEG transport stream (TS) packets or an MPEG program stream (PS).
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] The TS packets can then be transmitted using broadcasting techniques, such as those used in an ATSC and DVB.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] In order to provide mono *compatibility*, the NICAM signal is transmitted on a subcarrier alongside the sound carrier.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] This means that the FM or AM regular mono sound carrier is left alone for reception by monaural receivers.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] The NICAM packet (except for the header) is scrambled with a nine-bit pseudo-random bit-generator before transmission.
[src:packet-switching/network-packet] Making the NICAM bitstream look more like white noise is important because this reduces signal patterning on adjacent TV channels.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In telecommunications, **packet switching** is a method of grouping data into short messages in fixed format, i.e., *packets,* that are transmitted over a telecommunications network.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Packets consist of a header and a payload.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The header directs the packet to its destination, where the payload is extracted and used by an operating system, application software, or higher-layer protocols.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching is the primary basis for data communications in computer networks worldwide.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] During the early 1960s, American engineer Paul Baran developed a concept he called *distributed adaptive message block switching* as part of a research program at the RAND Corporation, funded by the United States Department of Defense.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] His proposal was to provide a fault-tolerant, efficient method for communication of voice messages using low-cost hardware to route the message blocks across a distributed network.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] His ideas contradicted then-established principles of pre-allocation of network bandwidth, exemplified by the development of telecommunications in the Bell System.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The new concept found little resonance among network implementers until the independent work of British computer scientist Donald Davies at the National Physical Laboratory beginning in 1965.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Davies developed the concept for data communication using software switches in a high-speed computer network and coined the term *packet switching*.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] His work inspired numerous packet switching networks in the decade following, including the incorporation of the concept into the design of the ARPANET in the United States and the CYCLADES network in France.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The ARPANET and CYCLADES were the primary precursor networks of the modern Internet.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching allows delivery of variable bit rate data streams, realized as sequences of short messages in fixed format, i.e.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] *packets*, over a computer network which allocates transmission resources as needed using statistical multiplexing or dynamic bandwidth allocation techniques.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] As they traverse networking hardware, such as switches and routers, packets are received, buffered, queued, and retransmitted (stored and forwarded), resulting in variable latency and throughput depending on link capacity and traffic load on the network.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Packet-based communication may be implemented with or without intermediate forwarding nodes (switches and routers).
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In case of a shared physical medium (such as radio or 10BASE5), the packets may be delivered according to a multiple access scheme.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching contrasts with another principal networking paradigm, circuit switching, a method which pre-allocates dedicated network bandwidth specifically for each communication session, each having a constant bit rate and latency between nodes.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] A packet switch has four components: input ports, output ports, routing processor, and switching fabric.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The concept of switching small blocks of data was invented independently by Paul Baran at the RAND Corporation during the early 1960s in the US and Donald Davies at the National Physical Laboratory (NPL) in the UK in 1965.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In the late 1950s, the US Air Force established a wide area network for the Semi-Automatic Ground Environment (SAGE) radar defense system.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Recognizing vulnerabilities in this network, the Air Force sought a system that might survive a nuclear attack to enable a response, thus diminishing the attractiveness of the first strike advantage by enemies (see Mutual assured destruction).
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In the early 1960s, Baran invented the concept of *distributed adaptive message block switching* in support of the Air Force initiative.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The concept was first presented to the Air Force in the summer of 1961 as briefing B-265, later published as RAND report P-2626 in 1962, and finally in report RM 3420 in 1964.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The reports describe a general architecture for a large-scale, distributed, survivable communications network.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The proposal was composed of three key ideas: use of a decentralized network with multiple paths between any two points; dividing user messages into *message blocks;* and delivery of these messages by store and forward switching.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Baran's network design was focused on high-speed digital communication of voice messages using hardware switches that were low-cost electronics.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Christopher Strachey, who became Oxford University's first Professor of Computation, filed a patent application in the United Kingdom for time-sharing in February 1959.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In June that year, he gave a paper "Time Sharing in Large Fast Computers" at the UNESCO Information Processing Conference in Paris where he passed the concept on to J.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Licklider (along with John McCarthy) was instrumental in the development of time-sharing.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] After conversations with Licklider about time-sharing with remote computers in 1965, Davies independently invented a similar data communication concept.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] His insight was to use short messages in fixed format with high data transmission rates to achieve rapid communications.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] He went on to develop a design for a hierarchical, high-speed computer network including interface computers and communication protocols.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] He coined the term *packet switching*, and proposed building a commercial nationwide data network in the UK.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] He gave a talk on the proposal in 1966, after which a person from the Ministry of Defence (MoD) told him about Baran's work.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Roger Scantlebury, a member of Davies' team, presented their work (and referenced that of Baran) at the October 1967 Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP).
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] At the conference, Scantlebury proposed packet switching for use in the ARPANET and persuaded Larry Roberts the economics were favorable to message switching.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Davies had chosen some of the same parameters for his original network design as did Baran, such as a packet size of 1024 bits.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Davies proposed that a local-area network should be built at the laboratory to serve the needs of NPL and prove the feasibility of packet switching.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] After a pilot experiment in early 1969, the NPL Data Communications Network began service in 1970.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Davies was invited to Japan to give a series of lectures on packet switching.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The NPL team carried out simulation work on datagrams and congestion in networks on a scale to provide data communication across the United Kingdom.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Larry Roberts made the key decisions in the request for proposal to build the ARPANET.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Roberts met Baran in February 1967, but did not discuss networks.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Roberts was known for making decisions quickly.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Immediately after SOSP, he incorporated Davies' concepts and designs for packet switching to enable the data communications on the network, and sought input from Baran.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] A contemporary of Roberts' from MIT, Leonard Kleinrock had researched the application of queueing theory in the field of message switching for his doctoral dissertation in 1961–62 and published it as a book in 1964.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Davies, in his 1966 paper on packet switching, applied Kleinrock's techniques to show that "there is an ample margin between the estimated performance of the [packet-switched] system and the stated requirement" in terms of a satisfactory response time for a human user.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] This addressed a key question about the viability of computer networking.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Larry Roberts brought Kleinrock into the ARPANET project informally in early 1967.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Roberts and Taylor recognized the issue of response time was important, but did not apply Kleinrock's methods to assess this and based their design on a store-and-forward system that was not intended for real-time computing.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] After SOSP, and after Roberts' direction to use packet switching, Kleinrock sought input from Baran and proposed to retain Baran and RAND as advisors.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The ARPANET working group assigned Kleinrock responsibility to prepare a report on software for the IMP.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In 1968, Roberts awarded Kleinrock a contract to establish a Network Measurement Center (NMC) at UCLA to measure and model the performance of packet switching in the ARPANET.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Bolt Beranek & Newman (BBN) won the contract to build the network.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Designed principally by Bob Kahn, it was the first wide-area packet-switched network with distributed control.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The BBN "IMP Guys" independently developed significant aspects of the network's internal operation, including the routing algorithm, flow control, software design, and network control.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The UCLA NMC and the BBN team also investigated network congestion.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The Network Working Group, led by Steve Crocker, a graduate student of Kleinrock's at UCLA, developed the host-to-host protocol, the Network Control Program, which was approved by Barry Wessler for ARPA, after he ordered certain more exotic elements to be dropped.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In 1970, Kleinrock extended his earlier analytic work on message switching to packet switching in the ARPANET.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The ARPANET was demonstrated at the International Conference on Computer Communication (ICCC) in Washington in October 1972.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] However, fundamental questions about the design of packet-switched networks remained.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Roberts presented the idea of packet switching to communication industry professionals in the early 1970s.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Before ARPANET was operating, they argued that the router buffers would quickly run out.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] After the ARPANET was operating, they argued that packet switching would never be economic without the government subsidy.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Baran had faced the same rejection and thus failed to convince the military to construct a packet switching network in the 1960s.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The CYCLADES network was designed by Louis Pouzin in the early 1970s to study internetworking.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] It was the first to implement the end-to-end principle of Davies, and make the host computers responsible for the reliable delivery of data on a packet-switched network, rather than this being a service of the network itself.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] His team was thus first to tackle the highly-complex problem of providing user applications with a reliable virtual circuit service while using a best-effort service, an early contribution to what will be the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Bob Metcalfe and others at Xerox PARC outlined the idea of Ethernet and the PARC Universal Packet (PUP) for internetworking.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In May 1974, Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn described the Transmission Control Program, an internetworking protocol for sharing resources using packet-switching among the nodes.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The specifications of the TCP were then published in RFC 675 (*Specification of Internet Transmission Control Program*), written by Vint Cerf, Yogen Dalal and Carl Sunshine in December 1974.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The X.25 protocol, developed by Rémi Després and others, was built on the concept of virtual circuits.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In the mid-late 1970s and early 1980s, national and international public data networks emerged using X.25 which was developed with participation from France, the UK, Japan, USA and Canada.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] It was complemented with X.75 to enable internetworking.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In the late 1970s, the monolithic Transmission Control Program was layered as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), atop the Internet Protocol (IP).
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Many Internet pioneers developed this into the Internet protocol suite and the associated Internet architecture and governance that emerged in the 1980s.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Leonard Kleinrock carried out theoretical work at UCLA during the 1970s analyzing throughput and delay in the ARPANET.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Kleinrock published hundreds of research papers, which ultimately launched a new field of research on the theory and application of queuing theory to computer networks.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] His work on hierarchical routing with student Farouk Kamoun became critical to the operation of the Internet.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching was shown to be optimal in the Huffman coding sense in 1978.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] For a period in the 1980s and early 1990s, the network engineering community was polarized over the implementation of competing protocol suites, commonly known as the Protocol Wars.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] It was unclear which of the Internet protocol suite and the OSI model would result in the best and most robust computer networks.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) VLSI (very-large-scale integration) technology led to the development of high-speed broadband packet switching during the 1980s–1990s.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In the 1978 special edition of the Proceedings of the IEEE on packet switching, Bob Kahn, the guest editor, wrote that "analysis has had little direct impact on the network design problem".
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In Roberts' paper on "Packet Switching Economics" for the L.M.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Ericsson prize for research in data communications in 1982, he referenced only Davies' 1967 paper for SOSP, not the work of Baran or Kleinrock.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Kleinrock's paper for the same prize was titled "Packet Switching Principles".
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In Roberts' 1986 conference paper on "The ARPANET & Computer Networks", he also cites Baran's 1964 paper and one of his own papers from 1966; but only references Kleinrock's work from the 1970s, which addressed the ARPANET.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] This paper was republished on the web by Roberts in 1995.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In 1997, along with seven other Internet pioneers, Roberts and Kleinrock co-wrote "Brief History of the Internet" published by the Internet Society.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In it, Kleinrock is described as having "published the first paper on packet switching theory in July 1961 and the first book on the subject in 1964".
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Many sources about the history of the Internet began to reflect these claims as uncontroversial facts.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] This became the subject of what Katie Hafner called a "paternity dispute" in The New York Times in 2001.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The disagreement about Kleinrock's contribution to packet switching escalated after a statement made on Kleinrock's profile on the UCLA Computer Science department website sometime in the 1990s.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Here, he was referred to as the "Inventor of the Internet Technology".
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The webpage's depictions of Kleinrock's achievements provoked anger among some early Internet pioneers.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The dispute over priority became a public issue after Donald Davies posthumously published a paper in 2001 in which he denied that Kleinrock's work in the early 1960s was related to packet switching, stating "I can find no evidence that he understood the principles of packet switching".
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Davies also described ARPANET project manager Larry Roberts as supporting Kleinrock, referring to Roberts' writings online and Kleinrock's UCLA webpage profile as "very misleading".
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Walter Isaacson wrote that Kleinrock's claims "led to an outcry among many of the other Internet pioneers, who publicly attacked Kleinrock and said that his brief mention of breaking messages into smaller pieces did not come close to being a proposal for packet switching".
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Davies' paper reignited a previous dispute over who deserves credit for getting the ARPANET online between engineers at Bolt, Beranek, and Newman (BBN) who had been involved in building and designing the ARPANET IMP on the one side, and ARPA-related researchers on the other.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] This earlier dispute is exemplified by BBN's Will Crowther, who in a 1990 oral history described Paul Baran's packet switching design (which he called hot-potato routing), as "crazy" and non-sensical, despite the ARPA team having advocated for it.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Former IPTO director Bob Taylor also joined the debate, stating that "authors who have interviewed dozens of Arpanet pioneers know very well that the Kleinrock-Roberts claims are not believed".
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Walter Isaacson notes that "until the mid-1990s Kleinrock had credited [Baran and Davies] with coming up with the idea of packet switching".
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] A subsequent version of Kleinrock's biography webpage was copyrighted in 2009 by Kleinrock.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] He was called on to defend his position over subsequent decades.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] A paper published in the journal *Internet Histories* in 2019 supported Kleinrock's view; the author interviewed Kleinrock and Roberts, and did not interview Scantlebury.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In 2023, Kleinrock acknowledged that his work published in the early 1960s was about message switching and claimed he was thinking about packet switching.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Primary sources and historians recognize Baran and Davies for independently inventing the concept of digital packet switching used in modern computer networking including the ARPANET and the Internet.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Kleinrock has received many awards for his ground-breaking applied mathematical research on packet switching, carried out in the 1970s, which was an extension of his pioneering work in the early 1960s on the optimization of message delays in communication networks.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Russell said "'Internet history' also suffers from a ... methodological, problem: it tends to be too close to its sources.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Many Internet pioneers are alive, active, and eager to shape the histories that describe their accomplishments.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Many museums and historians are equally eager to interview the pioneers and to publicize their stories".
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching may be classified into connectionless packet switching, using datagrams, and connection-oriented packet switching, using virtual circuits.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Examples of connectionless systems are Ethernet, IP, and the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Connection-oriented systems include X.25, Frame Relay, Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS), and TCP.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In connectionless mode, each packet is labeled with a destination address, source address, and port numbers.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] It may also be labeled with the sequence number of the packet.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] This information eliminates the need for a pre-established path to help the packet find its way to its destination, but means that more information is needed in the packet header, which is therefore larger.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The packets are routed individually, sometimes taking different paths, resulting in out-of-order delivery.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] At the destination, the original message may be reassembled in the correct order, based on the packet sequence numbers.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Thus, a virtual circuit carrying a byte stream is provided to the application by a transport layer protocol, although the network only provides a connectionless network layer service.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Connection-oriented transmission requires a setup phase to establish the parameters of communication before any packet is transferred.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The signaling protocols used for setup allow the application to specify its requirements and discover link parameters.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Acceptable values for service parameters may be negotiated.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The packets transferred may include a connection identifier rather than address information and the packet header can be smaller, as it only needs to contain this code and any information, such as length, timestamp, or sequence number, which is different for different packets.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In this case, address information is only transferred to each node during the connection setup phase, when the route to the destination is discovered and an entry is added to the switching table in each network node through which the connection passes.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] When a connection identifier is used, routing a packet requires the node to look up the connection identifier in a table.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Connection-oriented transport layer protocols such as TCP provide a connection-oriented service by using an underlying connectionless network.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In this case, the end-to-end principle dictates that the end nodes, not the network itself, are responsible for the connection-oriented behavior.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In telecommunication networks, packet switching is used to optimize the usage of channel capacity and increase robustness.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Compared to circuit switching, packet switching is highly dynamic, allocating channel capacity based on usage instead of explicit reservations.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] This can reduce wasted capacity caused by underutilized reservations at the cost of removing bandwidth guarantees.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] In practice, congestion control is generally used in IP networks to dynamically negotiate capacity between connections.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching may also increase the robustness of networks in the face of failures.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] If a node fails, connections do not need to be interrupted, as packets may be routed around the failure.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching is used in the Internet and most local area networks.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The Internet is implemented by the Internet Protocol Suite using a variety of link layer technologies.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] For example, Ethernet and Frame Relay are common.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Newer mobile phone technologies (e.g., GSM, LTE) also use packet switching.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching is associated with connectionless networking because, in these systems, no connection agreement needs to be established between communicating parties prior to exchanging data.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] X.25, the international CCITT standard of 1976, is a notable use of packet switching in that it provides to users a service of flow-controlled virtual circuits.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] These virtual circuits reliably carry variable-length packets with data order preservation.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] DATAPAC in Canada was the first public network to support X.25, followed by TRANSPAC in France.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) is another virtual circuit technology.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] It differs from X.25 in that it uses small fixed-length packets (cells), and that the network imposes no flow control to users.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Technologies such as MPLS and the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) create virtual circuits on top of datagram networks.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] MPLS and its predecessors, as well as ATM, have been called "fast packet" technologies.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] MPLS, indeed, has been called "ATM without cells".
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] Virtual circuits are especially useful in building robust failover mechanisms and allocating bandwidth for delay-sensitive applications.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] The work of Donald Davies in the late 1960s on data communication and computer network design became well known in the United States, Europe and Japan.
[src:packet-switching/packet-switching] This was the "cornerstone" that inspired numerous packet switching networks in the decade following.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] Store-and-forward switching centers are usually implemented in mobile service stations, where the messages that are sent from the sender are first sent to these centers.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] If the destination address isn't available, then the center stores this message and tries sending it later.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] This improves the probability of the message being delivered.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] In the other case, if the destination is available at that time, then the message is immediately sent.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] Store-and-forward networks predate the use of computers.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] Point-to-point teleprinter equipment was used to send messages, which were stored at the receiving end on punched paper tape at a relay center.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] A human operator at the center removed the message tape from the receiving machine, read the addressing information, and then sent it toward its destination on the appropriate outbound point-to-point teleprinter link.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] If the outbound link was in use, the operator placed the message in tape in a physical queue, usually consisting of a set of clips or hooks.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] A major relay center in the mid-1900s might have dozens of inbound and outbound teleprinters, scores of operators, and thousands of messages in the queues during peak periods.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] Operators referred to these centers as "torn-tape relay centers", a reference to removing the received message from the inbound teleprinter by tearing the paper tape to separate one message from the next.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] The U.S. military term for such a center was "Non-Automated Relay Center" (NARC).
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] In 1948, Western Union introduced Plan 55-A, the first automatic electromechanical store-and-forward message switching system.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] All message storage was performed by paper tape punches paired with paper tape readers, with a bin in between.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] It is very common for an email system using SMTP to accept a message, store it and then forward it on elsewhere.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] Although fully open mail relays are no longer common, not only does simple server-based forwarding work this way, but also many email filtering and automated electronic mailing lists services.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] SMS messages are first sent to a Short Message service center where they are stored temporarily before being forwarded to the intended recipient's phone, even if they are not currently reachable, allowing for delivery later when they come back online.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] Prior to the deployment of the Internet, computers were connected via a variety of point-to-point techniques, with many smaller computers using dial-up connections.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] The UUCP store-and-forward protocols allowed a message (typically e-mail) to move across the collection of computers and eventually reach its destination.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] Late in the 20th century, store-and-forward techniques evolved into packet switching, which replaced them for most purposes.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] FidoNet was an email store-and-forward system for bulletin board systems that peaked at 45,000 systems with millions of users across the world.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] The system was highly efficient, using the latest file compression and file transfer systems to aggressively drive down the cost of transmission on what was largely a hobby network.
[src:packet-switching/store-and-forward] The system was later modified to support public messages (forums) called EchoMail, which grew to about 8 MB a day, compressed.
